Equilateral triangle $ABC$ has been creased and folded so that vertex $A$ now rests at $A'$ on $\overline{BC}$ as shown.  If $BA' = 1$ and $A'C = 2,$ then find the length of crease $\overline{PQ}.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, Ap, B, C, P, Q;

A = 3*dir(60);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
Ap = (1,0);
P = 8/5*dir(60);
Q = C + 5/4*dir(120);

draw(B--C--Q--P--cycle);
draw(P--Ap--Q);
draw(P--A--Q,dashed);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$A'$", Ap, S);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, NE);
[/asy]

inference:
Let $x = BP$ and $y = CQ.$  Then $A'P = 1 - x$ and $A'Q = 2 - y.$

[asy]
unitsize(1 cm);

pair A, Ap, B, C, P, Q;

A = 3*dir(60);
Ap = (1,0);
B = (0,0);
C = (3,0);
P = 8/5*dir(60);
Q = C + 5/4*dir(120);

draw(B--C--Q--P--cycle);
draw(P--Ap--Q);
draw(P--A--Q,dashed);

label("$A$", A, N);
label("$A'$", Ap, S);
label("$B$", B, SW);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$P$", P, NW);
label("$Q$", Q, NE);
label("$x$", (B + P)/2, SW);
label("$y$", (C + Q)/2, SE);
label("$1 - x$", (Ap + P)/2, W);
label("$2 - y$", (Ap + Q)/2, E);
[/asy]

Since $\triangle PBA'$ and $\triangle QCA'$ are similar,
\[\frac{1 - x}{x} = \frac{2 - y}{y}.\]Then $y(1 - x) = x(2 - y),$ so $y - xy = 2x - xy,$ which means $y = 2x.$

Since $\triangle PBA'$ and $\triangle QCA'$ are 30-60-90 triangles,
\begin{align*}
PA' &= \frac{1 - x}{\sqrt{3}}, \\
QA' &= \frac{2 - y}{\sqrt{3}}.
\end{align*}Then
\[PQ = PA' + QA' = \frac{1 - x}{\sqrt{3}} + \frac{2 - y}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{3 - x - y}{\sqrt{3}} = \frac{3 - 3x}{\sqrt{3}} = \sqrt{3} (1 - x).\]By the Law of Cosines on triangle $BPA',$
\[1^2 = x^2 + \left( \frac{1 - x}{\sqrt{3}} \right)^2 - 2 \cdot x \cdot \frac{1 - x}{\sqrt{3}} \cdot \frac{1}{2}.\]This simplifies to $3x^2 - 4x + 1 = 0,$ which factors as $(3x - 1)(x - 1) = 0.$  Since $x < 1,$ $x = \frac{1}{3}.$

Therefore, $PQ = \sqrt{3} \left( 1 - \frac{1}{3} \right) = \boxed{\frac{2 \sqrt{3}}{3}}.$

